SCCST Science Teacher, Mary Lou DeCaprio, to teach Science lesson on “NJTV Learning Live” on Wednesday, May 27th at 11:00 AM

"NJTV Learning Live is a unique on-air instructional series to help kids learn remotely. Created by NJTV in partnership with the NJEA and the NJ Department of Education, hour-long classes for grades 3-6 are taught by NJ public school teachers."

How to access: Stream it on njtvonline.org/live or Channel 8 on NJ Cable (extension of WNET). Mrs. DeCaprio's Science lesson is set to air Wednesday, May 27th at 11 AM.

Brief description of Mrs. DeCaprio's lesson content:

In this lesson, students will learn that all that allows our planet to run can somehow be attributed to the Sun's power. Mrs. DeCaprio shows examples of harnessing the Sun's power in everyday life, and examines the layers of the Sun, its place in the Solar System, and what makes it the powerful force that it is.

#NewJerseyDOE
NJTV
WNET
NJEA

SCCST WILL CONTINUE TO BE CLOSED UNTIL AT LEAST FRIDAY, MAY 15 DUE TO COVID-19

The health and well-being of our staff and students is always our first priority.

At this time, the Sussex Charter School will continue to be closed until at least Friday, May 15. This decision has been made in consultation with superintendents from around the county. The Department of Health and the Department of Education have been consulted and informed of this decision. The situation regarding the school closures will be reassessed on a weekly basis and further information will be shared with our community as it is available.

Thank you for your cooperation

Noreen Lazariuk, Superintendent

SCCST CLOSED STARTING MONDAY, MARCH 16 UNTIL FRIDAY, MARCH 27 DUE TO COVID-19

The health and well-being of our staff and students is always our first priority. While there have not been any confirmed cases of COVID-19 in Sussex County as of this message, there is growing concern among many of local school leaders, parents, and community members that cases are inevitable. Just this afternoon during his address to the state Governor Phil Murphy used the term “inevitable” when discussing the need for school closures.

At this time, the Sussex Charter School will be closing for a period of ten days effective Monday, March 16, 2020 to Friday, March 27, 2020. The decision to close was made in consultation with superintendents from around the county. The Department of Health and the Department of Education have been consulted and informed of this decision. The situation regarding the school closures will be reassessed on a weekly basis and further information will be shared with our community as it is available.

Thank you for your cooperation

Noreen Lazariuk, Superintendent

This morning, the 8th grade class enjoyed a presentation from Mrs. Busniak, who not only is a parent who is very involved with our school and our PTO, but happens to be a Certified Professional Career Coach and a Certified Employment Interview Professional. We at Sussex Charter would like to thank Mrs. Busniak for taking time out of her schedule to come in to talk to our students.

post_text:
On December 8th, the 8th grade students of the Sussex County Charter School participated in a Motivational Assembly hosted by Ryan Benz. Ryan was able to complete the entire Appalachian Trail starting in Georgia and ending Maine by himself. It took him from May to September to finish the 2,189.8 mile Trail. He was on the trail for 187 days, and averaged 18.25 miles per day, even going through 6 pairs of shoes in the process. In his assembly to the students, he told them how hard it got sometimes but you just try and persevere. You set a goal and try to attain that goal. Just be mindful for the moments you are in. Ryan also told the students about Trail Angels, people who live near/off the Trail itself who offer food or housing to Trail Hikers who need that little bit extra help. This was an assembly that really hit home with a lot of the students.
#mindfulmoments

post_text:
On Tuesday, the Sussex County Charter 6th grade students went on a field trip to MindFit - a facility right here is Sparta, NJ that combines physical activity with STEM projects. Here is their philosophy:

"The seed of MindFit USA came from the widely-researched concepts of the many positive effects of exercise on the brain. High intensity exercise, done before, during, or after the learning process, have a very positive effect on an individual’s ability to learn and retain information. The fitness portion of MindFit USA is the “buy in” to be able to unlock the brain prior to utilizing the STEM lab. This has a profound affect on their creativity and productivity! Not only do our Fit-Gineers have access to the most advanced S.T.E.M. space in Sussex County, they are primed to maximize what they are going to get out of it! "

Check them out at www.mindfitusa.com

Motivational Monday!
Sussex Charter's NJHS has come up with a way to spread kindness around our school! Putting our own twist on the Kindness Rocks Project, we collaborated with Ms. Anderson and her art classes where students painted and designed rocks with kind gestures, quotes and/or sayings. We then placed the rocks around the gardens on our school's campus with a sign that read:
We've designed these rocks just for you!
If you find one that speaks to you:
- Take it into consideration
- Use it as inspiration
- Share one for motivation
- And help our garden grow!

post_text:
During this School Anti-Violence Awareness Week, DASI - Domestic Abuse and Sexual Assault Intervention Services came into the PE classes to talk to the students about Healthy Relationships. Here is some information from their Prevention and Education Team:
The Prevention and Education Team believes communities play a role in preventing sexual and intimate partner violence. We are committed to educating the community and raising awareness through prevention efforts to foster mutual respect and healthy relationships. Through these efforts, we can eliminate the conditions that cause and perpetuate sexual and domestic violence in our community. Today, we focused on respect and what constitutes a healthy relationship. We discussed the components of respect (recognition, equality, support, personal goals, empathy, connection, and trust) and why these are important. http://www.dasi.org/

post_text:
Thirst for Knowledge Thursday!

Over the last couple of weeks the 7th grade STEM classes have created scale models of the Banaue Rice Terraces located in the Philippines. Each group was required to do research on the benefits and reasons behind the construction and use of the rice terraces. The group were given constraints and only able to utilize specific materials. Each material used was worth a certain amount of points. The students main goal was to create a multi-level free standing tower to successfully transport 10 wooden beads from the top level to the bottom with the force of 1 liter of water. After each group presented their research and presentations, as a class we tested each groupâ€™s structure. They then found the difference of the points they earned for the amount of beads traveled down each layer of their structure and the amount of points in materials used to create their structures. #STEMClass #Science #Technology #Engineering #Math #STEMFun

post_text: Yesterday the students at Sussex Charter attended a presentation given by Detective Laird from the Sussex County Prosecutor's Office. Here is some new information about our Cubes in Space:

Today at NASA's Columbia Scientific Balloon Facility (Aug 22), they are trying to launch BOBCAT. This is NOT our flight. http://www.ustream.tv/channel/nasa-educational You can use this link to see outside operations. If BOBCAT successfully launches today, then LBD Test Flight #3/CiS RB-5 will have a launch attempt tomorrow!

You can also use this link to see where it is in flight once it launches: https://towerfts.csbf.nasa.gov/Maps/ConvGps696N.htm

As of the time I am typing this message, CSBF crew have the balloon stretched out on the tarmac awaiting it to be filled with helium from the truck. It's 5:40 AM there, and the sun has not risen. The video feed is a little grainy, but it will be better when the sun rises.

What special things do we do at Sussex Charter?

The kids had a blast visiting MindfitUSA this week during our STEM camp week on "Greenhouses & Robotics". They practiced physical fitness first to prep their brains for the creativity that followed, made up of building self- contained wick- based hydroponics. The instructors were great, and allowed the kids to examine the hydroponics towers and some of the 3D printed items that other students have created there. We are hoping to enjoy continued visits to the center in the future. They have even now created an online learning program. To learn more, visit
http://www.mindfitusa.com/ or their Facebook page.

post_text: 6th grade Solar Bag!
text: 6th grade Solar Bag!

post_text:
Teachable Tuesday!

In Mrs. Duncan’s 6th grade Science class we took advantage of a Sunny day. This Solar Bag was used to explore simple scientific concepts related to solar energy to more complex scientific laws of gases. Students now understand how color affects the temperature of an object exposed to sunlight. They also got to explain how the movement of hot air differs from the movement of cold air. We integrated mathematics using the metric system to find out the length, width, diameter, and volume of the Solar Bag. Some examples of technological devices such as solar pool covers, solar panels, solar powered calculators, and cars were discussed. Fun was had by all!

shared_text:
New Jersey Public Charter Schools Association
April 9, 2019 at 2:00 PM ·

Charter school trustees from more than a dozen schools throughout New Jersey participated on Saturday in the Fourth Annual NJCSA Charter Board Institute. Through a number of presentations and panel discussions, trustees learned about recent developments in the charter school sector, changes in school law and regulation, the impact of the charter school movement on social justice, and strategies around communications, advocacy, and media. Perhaps most importantly, trustees had the opportunity to meet informally with their peers from other schools to share practices and compare notes.

It is a testament to the dedication of these individuals that they would dedicate a beautiful April Saturday to refining their board governance skills and enhancing their understanding of this essential work.

Workout Wednesday!

Today, the PE Department set up a walking course inside the gym. Students are to walk about 2 steps per second (helps when there is Techno Music to help keep a beat!). A die will be rolled randomly. Here is what the students have to do when the number comes up:
6 - Push ups
5 - Sit ups
4 - Russian Twists
3 - Reverse Crunches
2 - Burpees
1 - Rocking Squat Get Up

The students performed these activities for roughly 20 minutes. If they kept pace, they walked close to a mile!

Teachable Tuesday!

On 3/19/19 Mrs. DeCaprio took students from her SWE Club and took them to Thor Labs in Newton for a Field Trip.
The girls learned about the grinding & polishing of lenses, both with mechanical & high tech modern equipment that used to perfect the surface of lenses,and also learned about glass fibers that are used for laser Optics purposes, how they're extruded and some of their applications. Thor's staff were very welcoming of us and also provided the students with a panel discussion with five of their women Engineers on staff. Our students represented Sussex Charter in a commendable fashion. Much was learned by all!

post_text:
Congratulations to our very own MaryLou DeCaprio who was selected to be a teacher featured in the February Newsletter for the Panasonic- sponsored Eco Project with her 6th graders

Project Ideas: Gardening
Students will be selecting an environmental issue and generating an Eco Project goal they can carry out for their project. One environmental issue that students may want to address is gardening.

Some Eco Project goals to consider:

Plant trees along a highway or busy roadway to prevent noise pollution
Plant wall shrubs and climbing plants by the walls of your school to help insulate the building
Install rainwater barrels at your school to collect water for trees and plants
Work with the school or another local organization to convert from gasoline-powered tools to push mowers, hand clippers and rakes to reduce air pollution
Start a local produce coop to reduce carbon emissions and support local farms and gardens.
http://www.foundationforimpactliteracyandlearning.org/ecocitizen/

post_text: What do we do for fun at Sussex Charter? Our school Climate Kids run events like Pin Guard! What is Pin Guard? A Dodge Ball like game where there are 5-6 players on a team that have to either knock down all 3 pins on the other teams side or get the other team out. This was a friends and family event so not only were our students involved, but their family and friends were too. We had a total of 9 teams compete. Congrats to the OG Charter Knights who won! Any money raised is going to help with the cost of the 8th grade trip to Boston.

post_text: The 8th grade STEM classes are currently building scale models of Tiny Homes. The introduction to this project was viewing/researching actual Tiny Homes and then working to create a scale model of a Tiny Homes of their own unique designs. The constraints for this project include: circuitry (a minimum of 4 working lights throughout the house), one motor (i.e. a working fan, motorized garage door, etc.) and one environmental friendly system.

post_text:
Teachable Tuesday

8th grade students in Ms. Kopy's Health classes have been researching information about marijuana and tobacco, specifically on the legalization on marijuana - since it is such a hot topic across the country. Students were to research both in for legalizing as well as why not to legalize it here in NJ. They needed to go through multiple research-based websites to come up with reasons for either side. Now Ms. Kopy has split the class in half and randomly placed them on a side of the topic (even if they do not agree with it). The students are now working together as teams to come up with the perfect defense for their side as they will have a debate at the end of the week.

post_text:
Throwback Thursday!
Let's check in on Katie MacKenzie!

I graduated from Sussex Charter in 2007. From there I went to Sussex Tech for 2 years, where I then transferred to Lenape Valley and graduated. I attended Sussex County Community College for 3 years, where I attained 2 separate associate degrees (Criminal Justice and Paralegal Studies) and graduated with high honors. Once completed, I transferred to Centenary University- Graduated Summa Cum Laude with my B.A. in Criminal Justice. When I took the LSAT in September of 2017, I passed with flying colors. I am currently applying to law schools currently and looking to Lobby after I graduate.
I've been working all throughout college. I was the youngest manager in the region for Radioshack. Managed a half a million dollar store at the age of 20. Due to this I was recruited by T-mobile a few years later and have been working there ever since.

I've been working all throughout college. I was the youngest manager in the region for Radioshack. Managed a half a million dollar store at the age of 20. Due to this I was recruited by T-mobile a few years later and have been working there ever since.

post_text:
Workout Wednesday!
Students were in stations today for 1 min 30 seconds. They had to do as much as they could at the station in the time allotted. The stations were:
Balancing and tap cones; Planks; Bounding/walking over benches; wall sits; hands/knees/feet station (crawling); Exerbands; Sit ups (any kind); Push ups (any kind); fast feet/jump over mini hurdles.
A group of students were able to wear the new heart rate monitors that were purchased with Grant Money from STEM. The IPad in the picture is showing the activity levels of those students in specific zones. The zones range in order from "least" to "greatest": Grey, Blue, Green, Gold, Red. We are trying to have them sustain their level of effort in the Green zone.

In the land of Sussex Charter STEM our students needed to create self-propelled cars. In this stunning example the students had set parameters to build a car that could cross their bridge created in an earlier project. In these videos we have the cars constructed and built by students, powered by a battery and run with motors. After a lesson on energy, switch connections and how electricity works, students were able to power their rides .

Here is an example of power, precision and the learning going on with STEM Class! Make sure to look at the videos as well!

Thirst for Knowledge Thursday!

In Mrs. Duncan’s 8th grade Science class we had a special guest speaker, Dr. Allen Weingartner and his papillion rescue dog, Eugene. Dr. Weingartner is a Doctor of Veterinary Medicine and has been practicing for over 30 years. Currently, he practices at Banfield Animal Hosital in Rockaway, NJ. The students were delighted to meet a real veterinarian. We just completed an animal anatomy unit covering organ systems and their functions. Dr. Weingartner showed us what a real animal examination is all about!!!

ONE TWO THREE FOUR, I DECLARE A PENNY WAR!

A new monthly PTO fundraiser at Sussex Charter School for Technology. It starts on the 1st and continues through the last day of each month. Each grade & faculty/staff have their own collection jug in which to raise coins for a ice cream party, pizza party, or other choice reward.

All coins count positively towards the goal, whereas all $bills count negatively.

RULES:
Each grade level (6-8) and faculty/staff all have their own jug for collecting money. Jugs will be located in the gym. GAIN POINTS by adding coins to your grade’s jug and LOWER the other grade’s total by adding bills to theirs.

PRIZES: The grade level (or faculty/staff) with the highest total gets an ice cream party on Friday the 20th during lunch.

POINTS:

Positive Negative:
Pennies (+1 pts) $1 dollar (-100 pts)
Nickels (+5 pts) $5 dollar (-500 pts)
Dimes (+10 pts) $10 dollar (-1000 pts)
Quarters (+25 pts)

Ready....Set....GO!!!!

post_text:
Some of the Happenings here at Sussex Charter:
The PE classes have started their Archery Unit through NASP. To coincide with the Unit, Mr. Fialcowitz had a former student Jadynn Doty come in to demonstrate her archery skills that she learned here through him. It became such a passion of hers that, as a junior in high school, she has sponsors and competes at the World level.

On Tuesday, Mrs. DiCaprio had paleontologists come for an assembly with the 6th and 7th graders. They showed how fossils are formed, as well as one of their bigger discoveries - Nixon the Triceratops!
